-- Lesson 1: Reading Performance Data
UPDATE lessons SET content = '<div class="lesson-content"><h2>Reading Performance Data</h2><h3>Understanding Your Campaign Metrics</h3><p>Reading performance data correctly is fundamental to Facebook advertising success. Metrics tell the story of campaign effectiveness and guide optimization decisions. This lesson teaches you how to interpret data accurately and make informed strategic choices.</p><h3>Key Performance Metrics Overview</h3><p>Reach: Unique users who saw ads. Impressions: Total ad views. Frequency: Average views per person. CPM: Cost per thousand impressions. CTR: Click-through rate. CPC: Cost per click. CPA: Cost per acquisition. ROAS: Return on ad spend. Each metric reveals different insights.</p><h3>Understanding Reach vs Impressions</h3><p>Reach counts unique users. Impressions count total views. High impressions with low reach means high frequency. Low reach limits campaign scale. Optimal frequency varies by objective. Awareness: 1-2 frequency acceptable. Conversion: 3-5 may be optimal. Monitor both metrics together for complete picture.</p><h3>Click-Through Rate (CTR)</h3><p>Percentage of impressions resulting in clicks. Indicates ad relevance and appeal. Higher CTR generally better. Benchmark varies by industry and objective. 1-2% typical for cold audiences. 3-5%+ for warm audiences. Low CTR suggests creative or targeting issues. Improve through testing and optimization.</p><h3>Cost Per Click (CPC)</h3><p>Amount paid per ad click. Lower CPC means more efficient traffic. Varies widely by industry and competition. Compare to industry benchmarks. Track trends over time. Rising CPC may indicate auction competition or ad fatigue. Optimize through better targeting and creative.</p><h3>Conversion Rate</h3><p>Percentage of clicks resulting in desired action. Critical for ROI calculation. Affected by landing page quality. Ad-to-page message match important. Track by campaign and audience. Low conversion rate despite good CTR indicates landing page issues. Optimize entire funnel, not just ads.</p><h3>Cost Per Acquisition (CPA)</h3><p>Cost to acquire one customer or conversion. Most important metric for direct response. Must be lower than customer lifetime value. Calculate including all costs. Compare across campaigns and channels. Optimize to reduce while maintaining volume. Balance cost and scale.</p><h3>Return on Ad Spend (ROAS)</h3><p>Revenue generated per dollar spent. E-commerce primary metric. Calculated as revenue divided by ad spend. 3:1 ROAS means $3 revenue per $1 spent. Minimum viable ROAS varies by business. Consider profit margins and other costs. Optimize for profitable ROAS, not just highest number.</p><h3>Frequency and Ad Fatigue</h3><p>Frequency shows average ad exposures per person. Too high causes ad fatigue. Performance declines with excessive frequency. CTR drops, CPC rises. Refresh creative when frequency exceeds 3-5. Expand audience to reduce frequency. Monitor closely for performance campaigns.</p><h3>Relevance Score and Quality Ranking</h3><p>Facebook rates ad quality and relevance. Higher scores mean lower costs. Based on expected engagement and feedback. Positive signals: clicks, conversions, shares. Negative signals: hides, reports. Improve through better targeting and creative. Quality directly impacts auction performance.</p><h3>Attribution Windows</h3><p>Time period for crediting conversions. 1-day click, 7-day click, 1-day view common. Longer windows show more conversions. Choose based on customer journey length. Consistent window for fair comparison. Understand what you are measuring. Attribution affects reported performance.</p><h3>Analyzing Campaign Performance</h3><p>Compare metrics to objectives. Awareness: focus on reach and CPM. Consideration: emphasize CTR and engagement. Conversion: prioritize CPA and ROAS. Identify top performers and underperformers. Look for patterns and trends. Make data-driven decisions.</p><h3>Segmentation Analysis</h3><p>Break down performance by dimensions. Age, gender, location, placement, device. Identify high-performing segments. Allocate budget accordingly. Exclude poor performers. Refine targeting based on insights. Segmentation reveals optimization opportunities.</p><h3>Time-Based Analysis</h3><p>Performance varies by time of day and day of week. Analyze hourly and daily patterns. Identify peak performance periods. Adjust ad scheduling accordingly. Consider time zone differences. Optimize delivery timing for better results.</p><h3>Competitive Benchmarking</h3><p>Compare performance to industry standards. WordStream and other sources publish benchmarks. Understand your relative performance. Set realistic goals based on benchmarks. Identify areas for improvement. Context matters for interpretation.</p><h3>Dashboard and Reporting</h3><p>Create custom dashboards for key metrics. Automated reporting saves time. Share insights with stakeholders. Visualize trends and patterns. Regular reporting cadence. Focus on actionable insights, not just numbers. Good reporting drives better decisions.</p><h3>Common Interpretation Mistakes</h3><p>Judging too quickly without sufficient data. Ignoring statistical significance. Comparing incomparable metrics. Not considering external factors. Optimizing for wrong metrics. Overreacting to short-term fluctuations. Missing the bigger picture. Avoid these pitfalls.</p><h3>Key Takeaways</h3><ul><li>Different metrics reveal different aspects of performance</li><li>Match metrics to campaign objectives</li><li>CTR, CPC, CPA, and ROAS are critical for most campaigns</li><li>Frequency monitoring prevents ad fatigue</li><li>Segmentation analysis uncovers optimization opportunities</li><li>Attribution windows affect reported conversions</li><li>Compare to benchmarks for context</li><li>Regular analysis and reporting essential for success</li></ul><p>Next lesson covers KPIs That Matter for different objectives.</p></div>'
WHERE title = 'Reading Performance Data' AND EXISTS (
    SELECT 1 FROM modules m JOIN courses c ON m.course_id = c.id 
    WHERE m.id = lessons.module_id AND c.title LIKE '%Facebook%Ads%Mastery%'
);

-- Lesson 2: KPIs That Matter
UPDATE lessons SET content = '<div class="lesson-content"><h2>KPIs That Matter</h2><h3>Focusing on Metrics That Drive Business Results</h3><p>Not all metrics are equally important. Key Performance Indicators (KPIs) are the metrics that directly impact business goals. This lesson helps you identify and focus on KPIs that truly matter for your specific objectives and business model.</p><h3>Defining KPIs vs Metrics</h3><p>Metrics: Any measurable data point. KPIs: Metrics directly tied to business objectives. All KPIs are metrics, but not all metrics are KPIs. KPIs align with strategic goals. Focus resources on improving KPIs. Avoid vanity metrics that look good but do not drive results.</p><h3>E-commerce KPIs</h3><p>Primary: ROAS and revenue. Secondary: CPA, conversion rate, average order value. Supporting: CTR, add-to-cart rate, checkout completion. Track customer lifetime value. Monitor repeat purchase rate. Optimize for profitable growth. Revenue and profitability are ultimate measures.</p><h3>Lead Generation KPIs</h3><p>Primary: Cost per lead and lead quality. Secondary: Conversion rate, form completion rate. Supporting: CTR, landing page engagement. Track lead-to-customer conversion. Calculate customer acquisition cost. Optimize for qualified leads, not just volume. Quality over quantity.</p><h3>Brand Awareness KPIs</h3><p>Primary: Reach and brand lift. Secondary: Frequency, video completion rate. Supporting: Engagement rate, share rate. Measure through brand lift studies. Track aided and unaided recall. Monitor sentiment changes. Awareness campaigns need different KPIs than direct response.</p><h3>App Install KPIs</h3><p>Primary: Cost per install and user retention. Secondary: In-app actions, session length. Supporting: CTR, install rate. Track Day 1, Day 7, Day 30 retention. Monitor in-app purchase rate. Optimize for quality users, not just installs. Lifetime value critical.</p><h3>Engagement Campaign KPIs</h3><p>Primary: Engagement rate and cost per engagement. Secondary: Comments, shares, saves. Supporting: Reach, video views. Track meaningful engagement, not just likes. Monitor community growth. Assess engagement quality. Engagement should support broader goals.</p><h3>Setting KPI Targets</h3><p>Base targets on business economics. Calculate break-even CPA or ROAS. Set stretch goals for optimization. Consider industry benchmarks. Account for seasonality. Realistic targets motivate teams. Unrealistic targets discourage. Adjust targets as you learn.</p><h3>North Star Metric</h3><p>Single most important metric for business. E-commerce: often ROAS or revenue. SaaS: typically MRR or user growth. Choose metric that best represents success. Align entire team around north star. All optimization serves this metric. Clarity drives focus.</p><h3>Leading vs Lagging Indicators</h3><p>Leading indicators predict future performance. CTR, engagement rate, add-to-cart rate. Lagging indicators show past results. Revenue, ROAS, customer count. Monitor both types. Leading indicators enable proactive optimization. Lagging indicators measure ultimate success.</p><h3>Cohort Analysis</h3><p>Group customers by acquisition time. Track performance over customer lifetime. Compare cohorts to identify trends. Understand long-term value. Optimize for cohort performance, not just initial conversion. Reveals true campaign effectiveness.</p><h3>Attribution and Multi-Touch</h3><p>Last-click attribution oversimplifies customer journey. Multi-touch attribution credits multiple touchpoints. Facebook may be assist, not last click. Understand full funnel contribution. Use platform-specific and cross-platform attribution. Complete picture requires multiple views.</p><h3>Balancing Multiple KPIs</h3><p>Optimizing one KPI may hurt another. Lower CPA might reduce scale. Higher ROAS might limit growth. Find optimal balance. Consider business stage and goals. Growth phase: prioritize scale. Maturity phase: prioritize efficiency. Balance evolves over time.</p><h3>KPI Dashboards</h3><p>Visualize KPIs for quick assessment. Real-time or daily updates. Share with stakeholders. Highlight trends and changes. Alert on threshold breaches. Good dashboards drive action. Focus on actionable insights.</p><h3>Reporting Cadence</h3><p>Daily monitoring for active campaigns. Weekly deep dives for optimization. Monthly strategic reviews. Quarterly business impact assessment. Match reporting frequency to decision-making needs. Avoid analysis paralysis. Act on insights.</p><h3>Common KPI Mistakes</h3><p>Tracking too many KPIs. Focusing on vanity metrics. Ignoring business economics. Not connecting ads to revenue. Comparing incompatible metrics. Changing KPIs too frequently. Not acting on insights. Avoid these errors.</p><h3>Evolving KPIs</h3><p>KPIs should evolve with business. Startup: focus on growth and learning. Scale-up: balance growth and efficiency. Mature: optimize profitability. Adjust KPIs as priorities change. Regular KPI reviews ensure alignment.</p><h3>Key Takeaways</h3><ul><li>KPIs are metrics directly tied to business objectives</li><li>Different business models require different KPIs</li><li>E-commerce: ROAS and revenue most important</li><li>Lead gen: cost per qualified lead critical</li><li>Choose north star metric for overall focus</li><li>Balance leading and lagging indicators</li><li>Multi-touch attribution provides complete picture</li><li>Evolve KPIs as business matures and priorities change</li></ul><p>Next lesson covers Scaling Strategies: Horizontal vs Vertical.</p></div>'
WHERE title = 'KPIs That Matter' AND EXISTS (
    SELECT 1 FROM modules m JOIN courses c ON m.course_id = c.id 
    WHERE m.id = lessons.module_id AND c.title LIKE '%Facebook%Ads%Mastery%'
);
